[1
Date: Thu, 13 Aug 1998 23:15:10 -0600
From: Barry Hill <hillbd@cadvision.com>
Source: Calgary Herald, Wednesday, August 12, 1998.

There have been more than three times the number of viral meningitis cases
in Calgary so far this year, compared with last year, according to the
city's deputy medical officer of health. Officials have been notified of
88 cases to the end of last month, compared with 24 in 1997. Seventy-five
of those have occurred since May but public health officials are not unduly
alarmed. Although 80% of cases in Calgary were hospitalized, this version
of the disease is rarely fatal.
The Provincial director of communicable disease control said Calgary was
the first to notice the recent increase but figures increased across the
province. It was also stated that there are periodic dramatic increases in
virus activity and that one must go back a number of years to see anything
comparable to this year. Because it is mainly a summer infection, Alberta
may not have seen the worst.
I will check to see what the isolated viruses have been and let you know.
--
Barry Hill MLT, ART (CSMLS) Clinical Laboratory Consulting
